    <div id="node-1160269" class="node node-teaser node-type-story"><div class="node-inner">



  

 <a href="/content/own-your-data-owncloud" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"><img src="http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/ufiles/imagecache/teaser/nodeimage/story/11563ownf1.jpg" alt="" title=""  class="imagecache imagecache-teaser" width="100" height="100" /></a> 
  
  


      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/content/own-your-data-owncloud" title="Own Your Data with OwnCloud">Own Your Data with OwnCloud</a>
    </h2>
  
  

  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
		By <a href="/users/shawn-powers" title="View user profile.">Shawn Powers</a>&nbsp;<!--|
		Oct 07, 2013 -->
     
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_276 first"><a href="/tag/cloud" rel="tag" title="">Cloud</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_895"><a href="/tag/owncloud" rel="tag" title="">OwnCloud</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_196 last active"><a href="/tag/tech-tips" rel="tag" title="" class="active">Tech Tips</a></li>
</ul></div>
      
  	 </div>
    </div>
  
  
    


  <div class="content">

    
    
            
                    <a href="/content/own-your-data-owncloud" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"></a>        
        

<p>I love Dropbox. I really do. With a Google AdWords campaign, and $50 or so, I was able to max out my free storage. That means I have around 24GB of free Dropbox storage to fiddle with. Granted, that's a lot, but in the grand scheme of things, 24GB isn't very much space.<span class="read-more"><a href="/content/own-your-data-owncloud"> more>></a></span></p>

  </div>



  <ul class="links inline"><li class="comment_comments first last"><a href="/content/own-your-data-owncloud#comments" title="Jump to the first comment of this posting.">5 comments</a></li>
</ul>
