 <a href="/content/one-tail-just-isnt-enough" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"><img src="http://www.linuxjournal.com/files/linuxjournal.com/ufiles/imagecache/teaser/nodeimage/story/11500multif1.png" alt="" title=""  class="imagecache imagecache-teaser" width="100" height="100" /></a> 
  
  


      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/content/one-tail-just-isnt-enough" title="One Tail Just Isn&#039;t Enough">One Tail Just Isn&#039;t Enough</a>
    </h2>
  
  

  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
		By <a href="/users/shawn-powers" title="View user profile.">Shawn Powers</a>&nbsp;<!--|
		Jun 07, 2013 -->
     
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"><ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_563 first"><a href="/tag/command-line" rel="tag" title="">command line</a></li>
<li class="taxonomy_term_196 last active"><a href="/tag/tech-tips" rel="tag" title="" class="active">Tech Tips</a></li>
</ul></div>
      
  	 </div>
    </div>
  
  
    


  <div class="content">

    
    
            
                    <a href="/content/one-tail-just-isnt-enough" class="imagecache imagecache-teaser imagecache-linked imagecache-teaser_linked"></a>        
        

<p>
Although it's difficult for me to look at this piece's title and not think of mutant
felines, it doesn't make the statement any less true. If you've ever used
the tail command on log files, you'll instantly appreciate multitail. My
friend (and LJ reader) Nick Danger introduced me to multitail, and I can't
believe how useful it is.<span class="read-more"><a href="/content/one-tail-just-isnt-enough"> more>></a></span></p>
